	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I rarely ever post anything here, because it's largely useless; but here I kinda felt obligated to participate.  Here's a simple truth of Everquest.<BR>
<BR>
There is no best class.<BR>
<BR>
The quality of your character isn't determined by your class or your race, or even your equipment- but by the player behind it.  Certain people excel at certain classes.  If you play a class that you're not good at playing then by default people will think your class is &quot;bad&quot; because you're not doing well.  On the other hand, an exceptional player can make their class do things no one ever thought of that class doing.<BR>
<BR>
In theory a lv34 shaman COULD beat a lv52 wizard, if the shaman knew the wizard's spellbook forward and backward and used walls and trees to break up his spells.  (Would take a stupid wizard- but it could be done.)<BR>
<BR>
Wizards have a lot of great uses post-50, not the least of which is the ability to nuke 100% resistant creatures such as black reavers (CoM), spite golems (PoH), gods, bosses (Venril, Trakanon, epic quest mobs), and highly resistant creatures like Amygdalan Knights (PoF) and dragons.  Each nuke is less mob life, which means less fight time, which means less damage done to your raiding team, which means better chance of success.  Wizards are considered completely essential for most critical raids against a single high-level target.<BR>
<BR>
Not to say we're the be-all end-all class of Norrath.  We're pathetic in dungeon combat, to be truthful- we do as much damage as the tanks, but only on a good charge of mana.  We excel at defusing crisis situations (whether by finishing off mobs or evacing the party) but we're inefficient against single mobs- where a pet caster can just /pet attack, fire one spell, and med out.  Our spell selection is debatably most limited of all the caster classes, we have one major utility- teleports- and we make some big sacrifices for that ability.<BR>
<BR>
But we excel at what we do...  Did you realize that every &quot;competing&quot; damage dealing class has a difficult choice to make, in terms of what class of spells to specialize in?  Mages are split between Conjure (summons, steel nukes) and Evoke (fire nukes).  Druids need to balance their healing (Alter) against damage (Conjure, Evoke).  I don't know the gory details behind shamans and necros, but I do know they have similar decisions.  Wizards, on the other hand, cast about 95% of their combat spells in their specialization class simply by default.  That's a big advantage.  (For those that don't know, Specialize decreases cast time, mana cost, and failure rate for all spells within its spell category.)<BR>
<BR>
Maybe someone will perk up and listen, if so, my work is done :)  Remember- it's only a game- have fun!<BR>
<BR>
Lv54 Channeler of Erollisi Marr
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
